<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-637-760  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 637 760.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  June 20 1990 n135 p22(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Graphics sector leads software market growth. (graphics,spreadsheets)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SpreadsheetsMarket AnalysisGrowthGraphics SoftwareSoftware PublishersComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Graphics sector leads software market growth The software industry grew by 11per cent over the last year, with the graphics and spreadsheets sectors ofthe market showing particular strength, according to a report from marketresearch firm Romtec.andM;The graphics arena was the most buoyant sector of the software market,enjoying a 36 per cent growth in unit sales to take 9 per cent of thesoftware market.andP;  The report, entitled UK Business Micro Marketplace1989-1994, shows that unit growth in spreadsheet sales reached 31 per cent.andM;&quot;Many more people are concentrating on using graphics in presentationstoday,&quot; explained Anna Scott, senior research analyst for Romtec.andP;  &quot;Visualimage is becoming more important.&quot;andP;  Lotus Freelance Plus and Harvard Graphicswere the biggest selling graphics packages.andP;  They held fifth and ninth placerespectively in the list of overall packages, where Lotus 1-2-3 once againled the field.andM;Despite a boost for graphics and spreadsheet software vendors, the Romtecfindings are less optimistic for companies selling integrated and databasesoftware: sales of integrated packages over the period slumped by 22 percent, while database programs dropped by 21 per cent.andM;According to Scott, the integrated market suffered from a lack of new orupgraded packages, while problems with dBase IV had an adverse effect on thedatabase market.andP;  &quot;But we expect database sales to pick up in the summer whenAshton-Tate starts shipping dBase IV 1.1,&quot; she said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>